🧰 Developer Guide – Rune Trade JSON

🔹 Top-Level Structure

{
  "Runes": {
    "Rune Name": [TradeEntry, ...],
    ...
  }
}

Each "Rune Name" maps to a list of trade entries. Each entry represents a seller offering that rune for specific items (“Ask”).

⸻

🔹 Trade Entry Format

Each trade entry contains:

{
  "seller": "string",             // Seller name
  "quantity": int,                // Number of this rune for sale
  "updated_at": "ISO 8601 time",  // Timestamp of trade
  "price": [                      // What the seller is asking for (can be single or multi)
    {
      "name": "string",           // Name of the item being requested
      "quantity": int             // How many of that item
    },
    ...
  ]
}


⸻

🔹 Sample Scenarios

✅ Example 1: Single price item

"Ist Rune": [
  {
    "seller": "kk_sama",
    "quantity": 1,
    "updated_at": "2025-05-21T04:52:43.189Z",
    "price": [
      { "name": "Perfect Amethyst", "quantity": 10 }
    ]
  }
]

✅ Example 2: AND trade (multi-item Ask)

{
  "seller": "DIABLO_666",
  "quantity": 20,
  "updated_at": "2025-05-21T03:59:40.573Z",
  "price": [
    { "name": "Jah Rune", "quantity": 1 },
    { "name": "Jah Rune", "quantity": 2 },
    { "name": "Ber Rune", "quantity": 1 }
  ]
}

This is an AND trade: buyer must offer all listed items.

❌ Example 3: No price (invalid or skipped)

{
  "seller": "rkdals1106",
  "quantity": 5,
  "updated_at": "2025-05-21T13:17:17.523Z",
  "price": []
}


